# Aria — local development environment
# Copy this file to `.env.local` (NOT committed; `.env.local` is git-ignored via `.env.*`)
# and paste the values from the Google Cloud Console step below.
#
# ============================================================================
# Google OAuth (Gmail + Calendar) — one-time setup
# ============================================================================
#
# Aria connects to your own Google account via a Desktop-app OAuth client.
# Because Aria is a local-first desktop tool, you must create your own OAuth
# client under your own GCP project. Aria does NOT ship with a shared client ID.
#
# Steps:
#   a. Go to https://console.cloud.google.com and create a new project named
#      "Aria (dev)".
#
#   b. APIs & Services → Library → Enable BOTH:
#        - "Gmail API"
#        - "Google Calendar API"
#
#   c. APIs & Services → OAuth consent screen
#        - User type: External
#        - App name: Aria
#        - User support email: adexdsamson@gmail.com
#        - Developer contact email: adexdsamson@gmail.com
#        - Scopes: add
#            https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly
#            https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.readonly
#        - Test users: add your own Google account (the one Aria will read).
#      Leave Publishing status as "Testing" for now.
#
#      NOTE: While in "Testing" status, refresh tokens expire after 7 days.
#      Aria's EMAIL-07 re-auth banner surfaces this inline when it happens.
#
#   d. APIs & Services → Credentials → Create credentials → OAuth client ID
#        - Application type: Desktop app
#        - Name: Aria desktop
#      Copy the resulting Client ID and Client secret.
#
#   e. Copy this file to `.env.local` and paste the values below.
#
#   f. Verify `.env.local` is git-ignored:
#        git status   # `.env.local` must NOT appear in tracked files
#
# ============================================================================

GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=
